> SQL injection is not avoided by escaping arguments, but by never mixing the command and user supplied arguments in the first place.<p>People see:<p><pre><code>  execute(&quot;select * from table where id = ?&quot;, id);
</code></pre>
as for the most part like:<p><pre><code>  execute(sprintf(&quot;select * from table where id = &#x27;%s&#x27;&quot;, escape(id)));
</code></pre>
Where `escape()` is written by &quot;smarter people&quot; and makes sure that `id` isn&#x27;t a string like this:<p><pre><code>  0&#x27;; delete all from user;&#x27;
</code></pre>
(e.g. turning it into `0&#x27;&#x27;; delete all from user;&#x27;&#x27;`). I realize that this isn&#x27;t what <i>actually</i> happens, but the general idea is that you are sanitizing your inputs.
